some times than others? What theories of legislative behavior and policymaking explain when repeals happen? Congress in Reverse is the first book to attempt to answer these questions. Jordan M. Ragusa and Nathaniel A. Birkhead examine when and why existing statutes are successfully “undone,” arguing that repeals are most common when the parties are united on the issue—which was not the case when it came to Obamacare for the Republican Party—and the majority party wins control of Congress after a long stint in the minority. By shifting focus from the making of laws to their un-making, Congress in Reverse opens up a new arena for studying legislative activity in Congress.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aRepeal of legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRepeal of legislationzUnited States. 0aUnited States.-Congress. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAffordable Care Act.  acongress.  alegislation.  apolitical parties.  apublic law.  arepeals.1 aBirkhead, Nathaniel A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2020z9783110704594oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831106930960 cprintz978022671733340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226717500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226717500/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  